I analyzed the logs. The application is **not failing because of the Oracle DDL errors**. Those are warnings generated by Hibernate during schema update. The **actual reason the application terminates is a missing Spring property**. 

## Root Cause (Application Failure)

The last exception in your log is the one that stops the application:

```text
BeanCreationException:
Error creating bean with name 'awsS3Config'

Caused by:
Could not resolve placeholder 'aws.accessKeyId'
```

Specifically:

```text
Could not resolve placeholder 'aws.accessKeyId'
in value "${aws.accessKeyId}"
```

This means your class probably contains something similar to:

```java
@Configuration
public class AwsS3Config {

    @Value("${aws.accessKeyId}")
    private String accessKeyId;

    @Value("${aws.secretAccessKey}")
    private String secretKey;

    ...
}
```

Spring cannot find the property:

```
aws.accessKeyId
```

so bean creation fails and Spring Boot exits.

